Day 3 – Git Commands


1. git init

Definition: Creates a new Git repository in the current folder by initializing Git tracking.

Example:

git init


2. git clone

Definition: Copies an existing remote repository from GitHub (or another Git server) to your local machine.

Example:

git clone https://github.com/user/project.git


3. git status

Definition: Shows the current state of the repository, including modified, staged, and untracked files.

Example:

git status


4. git add

Definition: Adds files to the staging area so they can be included in the next commit.

Example:

git add index.html

Or add all files:

git add .


5. git commit

Definition: Saves the staged changes as a snapshot in the Git history.

Example:

git commit -m "Added login page"


6. git log

Definition: Displays the history of commits made in the repository.

Example:

git log


7. git diff

Definition: Shows the differences between the current files and the last committed version.

Example:

git diff


8. git branch

Definition: Lists existing branches or creates a new branch.

Example (List branches):

git branch

Example (Create a branch):

git branch feature-login


9. git branch -a

Definition: Displays all local and remote branches.

Example:

git branch -a


10. git checkout

Definition: Switches to another branch or restores files.

Example:

git checkout feature-login


11. git switch

Definition: A modern command used to switch between branches.

Example:

git switch feature-login


12. git remote

Definition: Shows the remote repositories connected to your local repository.

Example:

git remote -v


13. git fetch

Definition: Downloads the latest changes from the remote repository without merging them.

Example:

git fetch


14. git fetch --all

Definition: Fetches updates from all configured remote repositories.

Example:

git fetch --all


15. git pull

Definition: Downloads and automatically merges changes from the remote repository into the current branch.

Example:

git pull origin main


16. git push

Definition: Uploads your local commits to the remote repository.

Example:

git push origin main


17. git merge

Definition: Combines changes from one branch into the current branch.

Example:

git merge feature-login


18. git rebase

Definition: Moves your branch commits on top of another branch to create a cleaner commit history.

Example:

git rebase main


19. git stash

Definition: Temporarily saves uncommitted changes without committing them.

Example:

git stash

Restore the changes:

git stash pop


20. git reset

Definition: Moves the current branch to a previous commit and can remove staged changes.

Example:

git reset HEAD~1


21. git revert

Definition: Creates a new commit that reverses the changes made by an earlier commit.

Example:

git revert abc1234


22. git tag

Definition: Creates a version label for a specific commit, often used for releases.

Example:

git tag v1.0


23. git clean

Definition: Removes untracked files and folders from the working directory.

Example:

git clean -f


24. git fork

Definition: A fork is a copy of another person's GitHub repository created under your own GitHub account. It allows you to make changes without affecting the original repository.

Example:

1. Open the repository on GitHub.

2. Click the Fork button.

3. A copy of the repository is created in your GitHub account.

4. Clone your fork:

git clone https://github.com/yourusername/project.git`
